"Camuffo D., Sturaro G.","Use of proxy-documentary and instrumental data to assess the risk factors leading to sea flooding in Venice",2004,"Global and Planetary Change","40","1-2",,"93","103",,,10.1016/S0921-8181(03)00100-0,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0347065204&partnerID=40&md5=41393df9764f572a9e34c0f11b8b4cb9","National Research Council, Inst. for Atmosph. Sci. and Climate, Climate and Microclimate Unit, 35127 Padua, Italy","Camuffo, D., National Research Council, Inst. for Atmosph. Sci. and Climate, Climate and Microclimate Unit, 35127 Padua, Italy; Sturaro, G., National Research Council, Inst. for Atmosph. Sci. and Climate, Climate and Microclimate Unit, 35127 Padua, Italy","Due to its geographical position, and because it was built at sea level, Venice is extremely sensitive to climate changes and, in the future, risks being submerged as a consequence of the expansion of oceanic water in response to global warming. A key problem is the increasing frequency of storm surges with the sea flooding the city (locally named acqua alta) that has reached an unsustainable level. After careful examination of both proxy documentary and instrumental data, it has been possible to reconstruct the extreme weather conditions and natural hazards, which have taken place in the last two millennia, with particular reference to surges. A key problem with proxy data from written sources is that periods with missing data may be misinterpreted as 'normal', or that inaccurate reporting may lead to duplication or even multiplication of events. For this reason, the accuracy of the proxy data has been checked by comparing it with other known events. An accurate series of the flood surges has been obtained combining instrumental observations (1872-2000) with documentary data for the previous period. The period of minimum solar activity of Spörer (1416-1534) was anomalous for surges. Not only have meteorologically perturbed periods been identified, but also the effects of the accelerated subsidence of the city and of certain works undertaken in the lagoon that varied the exchanges between the sea and the lagoon. The impact of subsidence and of the modified dynamical exchanges of the lagoon on the change in flooding frequency has been established. During the instrumental period, the tide gauge measured a 31-cm rise. The frequency of surges has dramatically increased since the 1960s, reaching about two flooding events per year, the greatest value since 792 AD. © 2003 Elsevier B.V. All rights reserved.","Flooding; Global warming; Sea level rise; Storm surges; Subsidence; Venice","coastal protection; flooding; global warming; risk assessment; sea level change; storm surge; subsidence; Eurasia; Europe; Italy; Southern Europe; Veneto; Venezia; Venice",,,,,,"(1983) Laguna, Lidi, Fiumi - Cinque Secoli di Gestione delle Acque, 152p. , Helvetia, Venice; Camuffo, D., Analysis of the Sea Surges at Venice from A.D. 782 to 1990 (1993) Theoretical and Applied Climatology, 47, pp. 1-14; Camuffo, D., Microclimate for cultural heritage (1998) Developments in Atmospheric Science, 23, 415p. , Elsevier, Amsterdam; Camuffo, D., Canaletto's paintings open a new window on the relative sea level rise in Venice (2001) Journal of Cultural Heritage, 4, pp. 227-281; Camuffo, D., Enzi, S., Critical analysis of archive sources for historical climatology of Northern Italy (1992) European Climate Reconstructed from Historical Documents: Methods and Results, 7 (SPEC. ISSUE), pp. 65-74. , Frenzel, B. (Ed.), Paleoclimate Research, Fischer Verlag, Stuttgart; Camuffo, D., Enzi, S., Climatic features during the Sporer and Maunder Minima (1995) Solar Output and Climate during the Holocene, pp. 105-124. , Frenzel, B. (Ed.), Fischer Verlag, Stuttgart; Camuffo, D., Sturaro, G., Sixty-cm submersion of Venice discovered thanks to Canaletto's paintings (2003) Climatic Change, 58, pp. 333-343; Carbognin, L., Gatto, P., Mozzi, G., Gambolati, G., Ricceri, G., New trend in the subsidence of Venice (1976) IAHS, 121, pp. 65-81; Carbognin, L., Gatto, P., Mozzi, G., Gambolati, G., Ricceri, G., Case history no. 9.3. Venice, Italy (1984) Guidebook to Studies of Land Subsidence Due to Ground-Water Withdrawal, International Hydrological Programme, pp. 161-174. , Poland, J.F. (Ed.), Working Group 8.4, UNESCO, Paris; Cocheo, C., Camuffo, D., Corrections of systematic errors and data homogenisation in the Padova series (1725-today) (2002) Climatic Change, 53 (1-3), pp. 77-100; Colacino, M., Dell'Osso, L., Monthly mean evaporation over the Mediterranean Sea (1977) Archiv fur Meteorologie, Geophysik und Bioklimatologie, 26 A, pp. 283-293; Eddy, J.A., Climate and the changing sun (1977) Climatic Change, 1, pp. 173-190; Enzi, S., Camuffo, D., Documentary sources of sea surges in Venice from A.D. 787 to 1867 (1995) Natural Hazards, 12, pp. 225-287; Favero, V., Parolini, R., Scattolin, M., (1988) Morfologia Storica della Laguna di Venezia, , Arsenale Ed. Venice; Frassetto, R., The subsidence and storm surge effects in Venice (1971) Consiglio Nazionale delle Ricerche, ISDGM, Tech. Report No. 54, 11p. , Venice; Giordani Soika, A., Meneghini, D., Di alcune modificazioni del clima di Venezia nell'ultimo trentennio-ripercussioni sul fenomeno dell'acqua alta (1970) Bollettino del Museo Civico di Storia Naturale di Venezia, 20-21, pp. 13-26; Lamb, H.H., (1972) Climate: Present, Past and Future, 1, 613p. , Methuen, London; Miozzi, E., (1969) Venezia Nei Secoli, 1-4. , Libeccio, Venice; Oppolzer, T.R., Canon der Finsternisse, Karl Gerold's Sohn (1887) Canon of Eclipses, , translated by O. Gingerich (1962): Dover Publication, New York; Piervitali, E., Colacino, M., Conte, M., Signals of climatic change in the central-western Mediterranean basin (1997) Theoretical and Applied Climatology, 58, pp. 211-219; Piervitali, E., Colacino, M., Conte, M., Rainfall over the Central-Western Mediterranean basin in the period 1951-1995: Part I. Precipitation trends (1998) Nuovo 